# Decision Framework

Use this framework for all training decisions.

## Step 1: Identify The Main Objective

Classify the current phase:

- base building
- fat loss support
- race preparation
- recovery block
- post-race transition
- injury prevention block
- travel mode
- maintenance

## Step 2: Assess Current State

Use available data:

- last 7 days training
- last 21 days trend
- sleep
- HR/HRV
- soreness
- pain
- stress
- nutrition
- subjective readiness

## Step 3: Select The Training Stress

Choose the minimum effective dose.

Do not add stress just because time is available.

## Step 4: Protect Key Adaptations

Do not let secondary training damage the main adaptation.

Examples:

- leg strength must not ruin key run sessions
- long gravel rides must not destroy the next run block
- calorie deficit must not compromise recovery during high load
- intensity must not be added when easy volume is not stable

## Step 5: Adjust The Plan

Use one of these actions:

- keep as planned
- reduce duration
- reduce intensity
- replace with Z1/Z2
- replace with mobility
- full rest
- deload the week

## Step 6: Explain The Trade-Off

Every recommendation should explain:

- what adaptation it targets
- what risk it avoids
- what to monitor next

## Conservative Default

When data is incomplete, choose the conservative option.
